text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts]]%0a%0a!Comparing English and Oneida%0a%0a:Author: BrandonN%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aOneida is missing the bilabial consonant sound%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI am comparing English and Oneida based on the absence of common consonants. When comparing the English language to other languages, the common consonant sounds that are typically missing are bilabials, fricatives, and nasals. English itself has all common consonant sounds present. The main comparison with Oneida is the absence of a bilabial sound, or the sound made when the lips come together and touch. As a result of the absent bilabial sound, Oneida is missing common consonant sounds to the English language that stems from plosives such as "p" and "b". Additionally, the Oneida language is also mostly missing the nasal consonant. As a result of the absent consonant sounds, Oneida only has consonants in the alveolar, velar, and glottal places.%0a%0aEnglish vastly differs from the Oneida language. As previously compared, the Oneida language lacks different sounds while English has a more exhaustive use of sounds ranging from bilabial to glottal. English specifically contains the common bilabial sounds of "p" and "b" which shows the clear difference from the Native American language. %0a%0aI am not familiar with the Oneida language in any capacity, but I was curious to see how a language would operate without the use of a common consonant sound. My first thought was that Oneida might use other consonant sounds more heavily missing one such as the bilabial, but in fact, it turned out to be the opposite. What made this language interesting is the small use of consonant sounds that focused on the alveolar, velar, and glottal. I am still curious as to how Oneida communicates or if it can communicate as well as other languages since it is missing consonant sounds compared to the English language. My overarching question to the Oneida language in addition to others is: Does missing common consonant sounds affect the quality of communication for the language?%0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://wals.info/chapter/18%0ahttps://wals.info/feature/18A#2/44.1/152.8%0ahttps://phoible.org/inventories/view/77#tipa%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210222-183619-78770#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Communication quality %0a-> - Gavin_D%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aTo provide my take on the question you ask at the end, I'd say not necessarily. Certainly, it's a simple fact that having fewer consonants and/ or vowels in a language limits the amount of possible sounds that can be produced. However, to circumvent this issue, users of a language can simply combine the sounds they do have in ways that wouldn't be valid in other languages.%0a%0aIn the document I link at the bottom, even a brief skim will show that in the Oneida language, there are a lot of combinations of consonants that would seem quite strange to us. For example, they have as options "ka", "klo", and "kwa", among many other examples that would be valid in English. However, they also have combinations like "kha", "kna","khya", and many more that would be against the rules of English.%0a%0aOn top of this, there are many aspects of language beyond the valid sounds themselves that go into creating meaning. A commonly known example is the use of pitch in mandarin. Specific to Oneida though, they have a far more complex system of stress than we're accustomed to in English, and they are also quite unique in making use of whispering in their language (for purposes beyond gossip). From the document I've been referring to, "Most words have two pronunciations depending on where%0athey occur in a sentence. Words that occur with other words immediately after them in%0athe same sentence have no whispering. But when those same words occur at the end of a%0asentence or when spoken in isolation, then the last syllable is typically whispered. Such%0awhispering is indicated in the writing system by underlining. "%0a%0aSource: https://www.uwgb.edu/UWGBCMS/media/Oneida-Language/files/teaching-grammar-revised4.pdf %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210222-183619-78770#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)
