o see how a language would operate without the use of a common consonant sound. My first thought was that Oneida might use other consonant sounds more heavily missing one such as the bilabial, but in fact, it turned out to be the opposite. What made this language interesting is the small use of consonant sounds that focused on the alveolar, velar, and glottal. I am still curious as to how Oneida communicates or if it can communicate as well as other languages since it is missing consonant sounds compared to the English language. My overarching question to the Oneida language in addition to others is: Does missing common consonant sounds affect the quality of communication for the language?%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://wals.info/chapter/18%0a%3c https://wals.info/feature/18A#2/44.1/152.8%0a%3c https://phoible.org/inventories/view/77#tipa%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: :)%0a%3c (:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
